   "families": [
      {
         "id": "ea9e4462-9e2e-4f53-81b1-64fbc48cffaa",
         "name": "Cultura Jōmon (縄文)",
         "history": [
            {
               "text": "As it is not possible to affirm that there is a relationship between the Paleolithic population and the people of the Jōmon culture (縄文), we will assume in this text that only the people of this culture are the most remote ancestors currently known of the present-day Japanese population (<htcite0>).\n\n#### The period of origin\n\nThe beginning of the Jōmon culture (縄文) in Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国) brought about an important discussion regarding the use of pottery by humans: was it first carried out in Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国), or was it developed on the continent and then brought to the archipelago (<htcite1>)?\n\nOne of the reasons why this discussion occurs is the preservation of materials on the islands due to, among other things, constant climatic changes.\n\nRegardless of whether the first pots were produced on the continent or on the island, we will accept the beginning of the Jōmon culture (縄文) as starting from pots dating to <htdate0> found at the Odai Yamamoto I site (<htcite2>), while emphasizing that despite this, it is possible to find sources that place the beginning of the period around <htdate1> (<htcite3>; <htcite4>).\n\nIn this text, we will explore the Jōmon culture (縄文) in six archaeological subperiods (Incipient, Initial, Early, Middle, Late, and Final) (<htcite5>; <htcite6>), without naming the people as usually occurs in genealogical texts, but bringing information related to them, because the lack of text does not mean they did not exist.\n\n#### The subperiods\n\nThe Jōmon culture (縄文) period was not uniform across the entire territory of Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国). According to the current understanding, the length of the subperiods is not the same across regions, and there are still scenarios such as Hokkaido, which did not have subperiods like the Incipient.\n\nIn addition to different beginnings, the end of the Jōmon (縄文) period also depends on the region of Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国) under study (<htcite7>; <htcite8>).\n\nIn the following, we will present one person for each of the mentioned time subperiods.",
