               "history": [
                  {
                     "text": "#### The Jōmon Family (縄文)\n\nSince we cannot name the people of this period, we will study the kinship between them through their DNA.\n\nBy studying the haplogroups of the Jōmon (縄文) from the Hokkaido region, Noboru Adachi and his collaborators identified distinct mitochondrial DNAs (mtDNA) (N9b, D4h2, G1b, and M7a) (<htcite0>). This leads us to a reflection:",
                     "source": [
                        {
                           "type": 1,
                           "uuid": "b0998bae-50f9-42ee-9b6c-0cd743429dac",
                           "text": "Adachi, N. et al.",
                           "page": "pp. 355",
                           "date_time": {
                              "type": "gregory",
                              "year": "2011",
                              "month": "",
                              "day": ""
                           }
                        }
                     ],
                     "date_time": null,
                     "isTable": false,
                     "imgdesc": "",
                     "format": "markdown",
                     "PostMention": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: We are a family</b><br /><br />Haplogroup D4h is found in the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>) (<htcite0>).<br /><br />Furthermore, we know that haplogroup D is also found in Siberia (<htcite1>; <htcite2>; <htcite3>).<br /><br />Are the letters chosen by the researchers a “coincidence”? Or, by studying us, did they manage to identify links between the mentioned populations?</div></div></center></p>",
                     "source": [
                        {
                           "type": 1,
                           "uuid": "b0998bae-50f9-42ee-9b6c-0cd743429dac",
                           "text": "Adachi, N. et al.",
                           "page": "pp. 355",
                           "date_time": {
                              "type": "gregory",
                              "year": "2011",
                              "month": "",
                              "day": ""
                           }
                        },
                        {
                           "type": 0,
                           "uuid": "92105889-8c32-4b59-93c8-79e43bd3e96f",
                           "text": "Starikovskaya, Elena B. et al.",
                           "page": "",
                           "date_time": {
                              "type": "gregory",
                              "year": "2025",
                              "month": "01",
                              "day": "07"
                           }
                        },
                        {
                           "type": 0,
                           "uuid": "0e33ca2b-e092-4fee-acc5-ed327575522d",
                           "text": "Dulik, Matthew C. et al.",
                           "page": "",
                           "date_time": {
                              "type": "gregory",
                              "year": "2012",
                              "month": "",
                              "day": ""
                           }
                        },
                        {
                           "type": 1,
                           "uuid": "1070f062-f6c1-4cc5-8732-83b31c8e5137",
                           "text": "History Tracers Team",
                           "page": "Indigenous Peoples of <i>Abya Yala</i> (America)",
                           "date_time": {
                              "type": "gregory",
                              "year": "2025",
                              "month": "",
                              "day": ""
                           }
                        }
                     ],
                     "date_time": null,
                     "isTable": false,
                     "imgdesc": "",
                     "format": "html",
                     "PostMention": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "text": "The understanding that the indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) originated from Asia has been proposed since the 16th century, according to the Gregorian calendar, in texts such as that of José de Acosta (<htcite0>). Confirmation and dating of this migration occurred later. Among the knowledge used to confirm it is genetics. As Noboru Adachi and his collaborators highlighted, an analysis was performed on the collected material and it was concluded that, although haplogroup D4h is found in populations of the Americas (*Abya Yala*), about 17,000 years ago the D4h2 subgroup diversified and is found only in Japan (Nippon koku o Nihon koku, 日本国) (<htcite1>).\n\nThus, we can affirm that, despite the distance, there is a relationship between different populations that possess mitochondrial DNA D4h and, consequently, haplogroup D (<htcite2>).\n\n#### Incipient Period\n\nIn the incipient period, the Japanese archipelago can be divided into two parts. The southern portion, which extends to the strait between Honshu — the largest Japanese island — and Hokkaido, already had pots, while Hokkaido still did not have them (<htcite3>).\n\nThe earliest evidence of pottery in Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国) has no decoration whatsoever, being made by coiling and with a flat base (<htcite4>). However, over time, other traditions were developed.\n\nFinally, it should be noted that, as pointed out by Oksana Yanshina, the reasons for this development of pottery are unknown. On the other hand, it is known that these populations became leaders in ceramic production (<htcite5>).",
                     "source": [
                        {
                           "type": 0,
                           "uuid": "c2f6de96-6589-4f66-858e-259bf3f3046a",
                           "text": "Acosta, José",
